00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:36.740
And it's like, well, what's
the status of the web today?

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:37.930
How are things
going with the web,

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:39.780
and how are things
going with standards?

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:41.785
ALEX DANILO: Well,
that's a great question.

00:01:41.785 --> 00:01:43.410
There's a lot of
activity in standards.

00:01:43.410 --> 00:01:44.880
I mean, there are
multiple groups.

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:46.942
There are multiple working
groups, as you know.

00:01:46.942 --> 00:01:49.400
Personally, I'm working on the
HTML standard at the moment.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:51.691
So I'm helping edit the spec
with a bunch of colleagues

00:01:51.691 --> 00:01:53.010
from other companies.

00:01:53.010 --> 00:01:55.760
And the way I kind of
view it is standards

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:58.200
are really important, because
without standards, things

00:01:58.200 --> 00:01:59.290
don't work right.

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:02.120
If I write a web page and I
just bash the markup together,

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:03.610
it might work in
my browser, but it

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:05.040
won't work in other browsers.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:06.540
And the way it works
across browsers

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:07.706
is through standards, right?

00:02:07.706 --> 00:02:09.990
So that the browsers
implement the same thing.

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:12.279
And if I implement my page
adhering to the standards,

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:13.570
it will work everywhere, right?

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:15.390
LAURENCE MORONEY: And it's
important to get things working

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:16.740
the same way everywhere, right?

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:19.800
I remember the old story about--
wasn't it like a Mars mission?

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:22.400
Where the Europeans
measured it in metric,

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:24.250
and we measured it in imperial.

00:02:24.250 --> 00:02:26.540
And instead of
landing, it went splat.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:28.090
ALEX DANILO: Slammed
in the planet.

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:29.452
All over.

00:02:29.452 --> 00:02:31.260
Same thing happened
quite a long time

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:33.680
ago with the Fortran
program as well.

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:36.474
Where it was like people
decided to use Fortran for one

00:02:36.474 --> 00:02:37.640
of the space probes in NASA.

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:39.848
